Here's a minimal API endpoint handling multipart form uploads with images and a description:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the multipart form; set the same 50 MB cap on buffering
    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync(new FormOptions
    {
        MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 50 * 1024 * 1024
    });

    var description = form["description"].ToString();
    var files = form.Files.GetFiles("images"); // matches <input name="images">

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No images provided.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        // Validate content type
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var destPath = Path.Combine("Uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("Uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(destPath);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(destPath);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, uploadedFiles = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();          // needed for minimal APIs accepting forms without a token

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** — `MaxRequestBodySize` must be raised (default is ~30 MB).
- **`FormOptions.MultipartBodyLengthLimit`** — independently caps multipart field sizes.
- **`form.Files.GetFiles("images")`** — pulls all files matching the form field name.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — required in .NET 8+ for form-accepting minimal API endpoints unless you're sending an antiforgery token.

A matching `curl` test:

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=Vacation photos" \
  -F "images=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "images=@photo2.png"
```
